::USGOV-U01-P01::What is the main purpose of government? {
~To remove all rules#Incorrect. Governments create and enforce rules.
=To maintain order and provide services#Correct. This is a core idea from Unit 01.
~To eliminate all conflict#Incorrect. Governments manage conflict, not eliminate it.
~To avoid decision-making#Incorrect. Governments make decisions for society.
}

::USGOV-U01-P02::Why do governments form? {
~To create confusion#Incorrect. Governments create structure.
~To remove cooperation#Incorrect. Governments support cooperation.
=To maintain order and protect people#Correct. This reflects Lesson 2.
~To eliminate all laws#Incorrect. Governments create laws.
}

::USGOV-U01-P03::What does power mean in government? {
~The right to vote#Incorrect. That is a civic right, not power.
=The ability to influence or control#Correct. This is the definition of power.
~A type of law#Incorrect. Power is not a law.
~A form of government#Incorrect. Power exists within governments.
}

::USGOV-U01-P04::What is authority? {
~The ability to ignore laws#Incorrect. Authority is not ignoring rules.
~Public disagreement#Incorrect. Authority is not disagreement.
~A government service#Incorrect. Authority is not a service.
=The recognized right to use power#Correct. This is the definition of authority.
}

::USGOV-U01-P05::Legitimacy means people accept authority as rightful. {
True#Correct. Legitimacy depends on public acceptance.
False#Incorrect. That is the definition of legitimacy.
####Additional source choices preserved from JSON metadata context: "Partially true" - Incorrect. This is a clear true statement. "Not enough information" - Incorrect. The concept is clearly defined.
}

::USGOV-U01-P06::Which best describes citizenship? {
~Avoiding all laws#Incorrect. Citizenship includes following laws.
~Ignoring civic duties#Incorrect. Citizenship includes responsibilities.
~Controlling government completely#Incorrect. Citizenship does not mean unlimited control.
=Being a member of a country with rights and responsibilities#Correct. This is the definition of citizenship.
}

::USGOV-U01-P07::Which is an example of civic responsibility? {
=Voting and staying informed#Correct. These are key civic responsibilities.
~Breaking laws when convenient#Incorrect. That is not responsible behavior.
~Avoiding all participation#Incorrect. Civic responsibility involves participation.
~Ignoring community issues#Incorrect. Citizens should engage with issues.
}

::USGOV-U01-P08::Which example shows government providing a service? {
~A student doing homework#Incorrect. That is not a government service.
~A person watching TV#Incorrect. This is not a government action.
=A city maintaining public roads#Correct. Infrastructure is a public service.
~A business setting prices#Incorrect. That is a private sector activity.
}
